### 1.4 Public vs. Private IP

**30-second interview answer:**
> "Private IPs are used for internal communication within a network — your laptop's IP on the office network is private. Public IPs are assigned by ISPs and used for internet-facing communication. Private IPs cannot go directly to the internet — they use NAT (Network Address Translation) via the router to borrow the public IP."

**Private IP ranges (memorise these):**

| Class | Range | Common use |
|-------|-------|-----------|
| A | `10.0.0.0 – 10.255.255.255` | Large enterprises |
| B | `172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255` | Medium networks |
| C | `192.168.0.0 – 192.168.255.255` | Home/small office |

**Special addresses:**
- `127.0.0.1` = Loopback (test your own NIC)
- `169.254.x.x` = APIPA (DHCP failed)
- `0.0.0.0` = Default/unassigned

