### 5.6 "What's the difference between a Distribution List and a Security Group?"

> "A Distribution List is email-only — you send one email and it goes to all members. It can't be used for permissions. A Security Group is used for permissions — controlling who can access a shared drive, SharePoint site, or application. Security groups can also be mail-enabled, giving you both functions. At L1/L2 I create and manage both in the M365 Admin Centre."

---

### 5.7 "What is Group Policy?"

> "Group Policy is an Active Directory feature that lets administrators manage and configure settings for users and computers across the entire organisation from one place. Instead of configuring 100 PCs individually, I create a GPO and link it to an OU — the settings apply automatically. I've used it to enforce desktop wallpapers, map network drives, push software, and configure security settings like password complexity. I use `gpupdate /force` on a client machine to apply changes immediately without waiting."

---

### 5.8 "What is RAID?"

> "RAID stands for Redundant Array of Independent Disks. It combines multiple physical hard drives into a single logical unit to provide either data redundancy, improved performance, or both. The most common ones at L1/L2 level are RAID 1 (mirroring — data written to two drives simultaneously, so if one fails the other has everything) and RAID 5 (striping with parity — good balance of performance and redundancy). If a server RAID alarm goes off, I'd identify the failed disk and hot-swap it so the array can rebuild."

---

### 5.9 "What is a Virtual Machine?"

> "A VM is a software emulation of a physical computer. It runs on a hypervisor — either Type 1 like VMware ESXi or Hyper-V which runs directly on hardware (used in production), or Type 2 like VMware Workstation which runs on top of an OS (used for testing). VMs let you run multiple isolated systems on a single physical host, which saves hardware costs and makes snapshots possible — you can revert to a previous state if an update breaks something."

